Just did a little back of the napkin math on this.

At the current wage if you work 30 hours, you‚Äôre paid $66. If the 66.67% rule from 1989 was still in place, you‚Äôd make $185. Your boss is keeping an extra $119 that should be yours. https://t.co/aico8ndyIU

This is how policy decisions help bosses at the expense of workers.

Raise the minimum wage to $15 and end the tipped wage.

Because the state allowed the gap between the tipped wage and the minimum wage to grow, employers get away with contributing just 24% of a tipped workers minimum wage.

Now worker's tips have to cover 76% of their minimum wage. In 1989, tips only covered 33%.

In 30 years tipped workers have lost ground. They used to be paid 66.67% of the minimum wage. Now they're only paid 24%.

But tipped workers are still required to make minimum wage when their hourly wage and hourly tips are combined.

In 2009, of states that had a tipped wage higher than the federal minimum, Delaware's tipped workers got the lowest share of state minimum wage‚Äî31%.

Now that minimum wage has increased to $9.25/hr, tipped workers are doing even worse. They're making only 24% of the minimum wage. https://t.co/SHJKlPfqBe

Tipped workers used to be paid 66.67% of the minimum wage. So, as the minimum wage went up the tipped wage did too.

But in 1989, our General Assembly changed the tipped wage to a flat $2.23/hour. It hasn't gone up since.

In Delaware, the minimum wage for tipped workers has not gone up for more than 30 years.

It was $2.23/hr then and it's $2.23/hr now.
